                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d510">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">550.S1/1115: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Roosevelt</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="15" xml:id="d510fn15">Transmitted to the Chairman of the American
                        delegation as telegram No. 99, July 4, 10 a.m.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>U. S. S. “<hi rend="smallcaps">Indianapolis</hi>,”</placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-07-03T23:00:00-06:00">July 3, 1933—11
                            p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received July 4—1:18 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>22. Your 93.<note n="15a" xml:id="d510fn15a">July 3, noon; not printed.</note> In
                    discussing effect of recovery legislation on instructions with Cabinet it would
                    be helpful to us if you could suggest <pb facs="0782" n="680" xml:id="pg_680"/>
                    to us more particularly in what way and where you fear possible conflict between
                    instructions and general policy.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Roosevelt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
